description: The screenshot displays a standard Windows XP desktop with a black background. The Start button is visible in the bottom left corner, and the Recycle Bin icon is in the bottom right. A white mouse cursor, appearing as an arrow, is positioned in the top left corner of the screen. No other windows or dialog boxes are open.

The screenshot shows a standard Windows XP desktop with a black background. A context menu is open, displaying options such as "Arrange Icons By", "Refresh", "Paste", "Paste Shortcut", "New", and "Properties". The mouse cursor, a white arrow, hovers over the context menu. The Start button and Recycle Bin icon remain in the bottom left and right corners, respectively. 

New UI Elements:
- A context menu is now visible near the top left corner of the screen.

The menu, titled with a black bar, offers several options: "Arrange Icons By," "Refresh," "Paste," "Paste Shortcut," "New," and "Properties." The "Properties" option is highlighted in purple, indicating it is being selected by the user's mouse cursor, represented by a white arrow.

The screenshot shows the "Display Properties" window open on the Windows XP desktop. The "Themes" tab is selected. The context menu is no longer visible. 
- New UI Elements: The "Display Properties" window is now present. It has several tabs: "Themes", "Desktop", "Screen Saver", "Appearance", and "Settings". The "Themes" tab is currently selected. This window also features buttons for "OK", "Cancel", "Apply", "Save As...", and "Delete". There are also two boxes labeled "Theme" and "Sample", with drop-down menus and selection options within them.
- Missing UI Elements: The context menu from the initial description is no longer present.

The screenshot displays the "Display Properties" window in Windows XP, specifically the "Screen Saver" tab. 

At the top, a series of tabs allow navigation through different display settings: "Themes," "Desktop," "Screen Saver," "Appearance," and "Settings." The "Screen Saver" tab is currently active.

Below, a dropdown menu labeled "Theme:" allows the user to choose a visual theme for their desktop. The currently selected theme is "Windows Classic (Modified)." 

To the right of the "Theme" dropdown menu, a "Save As..." button enables users to save a customized theme. Next to it, a "Delete" button allows for the removal of a previously saved theme.

Below the "Theme" section, a "Sample" area provides a preview of the selected theme's window appearance. It showcases "Active Window" and "Window Text" elements. 

At the bottom of the window, standard buttons are visible: "OK" to apply changes and close the window, "Cancel" to discard changes and close the window, and "Apply" to apply changes without closing the window.

The screenshot displays the "Display Properties" window, focused on the "Screen Saver" tab. The most noticeable difference is that the "Screen saver" dropdown menu now displays "None." Additionally, a "Power..." button is now visible below the "Monitor power" text. 

The "Theme:" dropdown menu, "Save As..." and "Delete" buttons, and the "Sample" area described in the initial state are no longer present in the screenshot.

The "Display Properties" window is open, displaying the "Screen Saver" tab. 

The "Screen saver" dropdown menu currently displays "Windows XP", indicating the selected screen saver. A dropdown arrow is visible on the right side of the menu, allowing the user to expand and choose from other available screen savers. 

To the right are the "Settings" and "Preview" buttons. The "Settings" button likely allows customization of the currently selected "Windows XP" screen saver. The "Preview" button likely triggers a temporary display of the chosen screen saver within the monitor preview box above. 

Below, a text field labeled "Wait:" is paired with an incremental counter using the up and down arrows to specify a time value in minutes. This likely determines the duration of inactivity before the screen saver activates.  

An unchecked "On resume, password protect" checkbox is located to the right. This option, when enabled, likely enforces password authentication upon returning from the screen saver. 

The "Monitor power" section provides instructions to adjust monitor power settings and save energy by clicking the "Power" button. This suggests further customization options related to monitor power management are available within a separate window accessed by clicking the "Power" button. 

At the bottom of the window are the standard "OK", "Cancel", and "Apply" buttons. The "OK" button likely saves any changes and closes the window. The "Cancel" button likely discards any changes and closes the window. The "Apply" button likely applies any changes without closing the window.

The "Display Properties" window remains open, specifically the "Screen Saver" tab. 

The "Screen saver" dropdown menu is expanded, displaying a list of available screen savers: "Windows XP", "Marquee", "My Pictures Slideshow", "Mystify", "Starfield", and "Windows XP" again. The last option, "Windows XP", is highlighted.

The screenshot displays the "Power Options Properties" window within the Windows XP "Display Properties" settings. 

The active window, "Power Options Properties", is organized into several key areas:

* **Power Schemes:** The currently selected scheme is "Home/Office Desk", displayed in a dropdown menu. This menu allows users to choose from pre-set power plans or custom ones. The "Save As.." button allows saving the current settings as a new custom scheme, while the "Delete" button allows deleting a custom scheme. 
* **Settings for Home/Office Desk power scheme:** This section lists various power management options configurable within the selected scheme. 
    * **"Turn off monitor:"** This option, currently set to "Never" using the dropdown menu, controls the time after which the monitor will be turned off automatically.
    * **Other power options:** The remaining dropdown menus, "Turn off hard disks:", "System standby:", and "System hibernates:", all set to "Never", control their respective power-saving features. 
* **Action Buttons:** Located at the bottom of the window are three buttons:
    * **OK:** Confirms the changes made within the "Power Options Properties" window and applies them to the system.
    * **Cancel:** Discards any changes made within the window and reverts to the previous settings.
    * **Apply:** Immediately applies the changes made within the window without closing it.
